      <h1>Not the Same New York Yankees</h1>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-12 text-center px-4">
      <p class="subheader">Where the Yankees were at the beginning of the 2000s and where the Yankees were 20 years later</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row justify-content-center mb-4">
    <div class="col-12 col-md-10 px-4">
      <p>
      The Yankees are the most historic team in all of sports: 27 World Series titles, 21 AL East Division championships, 22 jersey numbers retired, and 61 Hall of Famers between players, managers, and executives. Despite this, the first 20 years of the 21st century have been a roller coaster of success. Over that time, the Yankees have proven to be one of, if not the most dominant team in MLB. But, after the first 10 years of the 21st century, the success was not replicated. Heading into the year 2000, the New York Yankees were the team in Major League Baseball. The Yanks had won three championships out of the last four seasons and showed no signs of slowing down in the near future. And through the first 10 years of the 2000s, the dominance continued with some unfortunate postseason luck.  
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row mb-2 px-2">
    <div class="col-12">
      <iframe src='https://cdn.knightlab.com/libs/timeline3/latest/embed/index.html?source=v2%3A2PACX-1vRPeWDyaoZ1ASaUM_pXM9QScESGkMaWmjZ0g8jCMpBHzrAT9u3NxGtakzZDiieUoQStQHV9va0e49cL&font=Default&lang=en&initial_zoom=2&width=100%25&height=650'
        width='100%' height='650' webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen frameborder='0' style="border:none;">
