<div class="row justify-content-center mb-4">
  <div class="col-12 col-md-10 px-4">
    <p>
      The key to the Yankees' success over the last 20 years was the offense. Outside of a four-year dip in production, the New York offense was year in and year out one of the best in the league. From 2000 to 2010, when the Yankees were at the peak of their powers, the offense was wearing the infinity gauntlet. During that time, the Yankees averaged the most runs per game in five of the 10 seasons. Plus, they were second in the league in two other seasons.
    </p>
    <p>
      Meanwhile, outside of the 2013-2016 seasons, the Yankees picked up right where they had left off the previous decade. The 2011-2020 time period got off to a booming start. The Yanks had the second-best offense in 2011 and the second-best in 2012. Then the rebuild began. Over the next four years, the Yankees had to reconstruct their roster as long-tenured players began to leave the team for other teams, get older and retire, or just regress due to injuries and/or age. Players like Derek Jeter and Jorge Posada were getting older. Second baseman Robinson Cano signed a 10-year contract with the Seattle Mariners, coming off four straight All-Star teams with the Yankees. And a player such as Alex Rodriguez began to show his age and never really returned to the player he was before 2013. So, after four years of retooling, the Yankees turned to their "baby bombers," and they mashed.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

