<div class="row justify-content-center mb-4">
  <div class="col-12 col-md-10 px-4">
    <p>
      Starting in 2017, the Yankees started the "Baby Bomber" era. After a complete roster overhaul, New York was out to prove that the young guys would come in and end an eight-year drought in the World Series. And, over the next four seasons, the offense lived up to the challenge. The Yankees had a top-five offense in each season to round the decade, in terms of runs per game. Specifically, they were almost the best, literally, finishing in second for runs per game from 2017 to 2019, with an average of 5.5 runs per game. And the way they did it was with the long ball.
    </p>
    <p>
      The new influx of talent includes young guys like former first-round pick Aaron Judge, Gleyber Torres, and Gary Sanchez. Starting with Judge, the rookie burst onto the scene with 52 home runs, breaking the all-time rookie record for home runs in a season. But, he backed it up with 27 long balls in each of the next two seasons, despite missing a third of the season. Torres blasted 38 home runs in 2018, which was the sixth most in the American League and the most by a second baseman that season. Sanchez was very consistent, hitting at least 18 home runs over those four seasons (33 in 2017 and 34 in 2019). Plus, the Yankees added reigning 2017 MVP Giancarlo Stanton from the Marlins, who hit 38 in 2018, and missed most of the 2019 season due to injuries. But the Yankees started to smash records. At the end of the 2020 season, 2019 was first (306), 2018 was second (267), and 2017 was third (245) for the most team home runs in a single season in Yankees history. Despite all of the offensive success over the last 20 years, where did it go wrong? One word: pitching.
    </p>
  </div>
