<div class="row justify-content-center mb-4">
  <div class="col-12 col-md-10 px-4">
    <p>
      Legendary former Alabama football head coach Paul "Bear" Bryant once said, "Offense wins games, but defense wins championships". Well, that is true for the Yankees over the last 21 seasons. New York wanted to lean on an approach that backed up the franchise's nickname of the "Bronx Bombers", and hoped that an average pitching staff would get them through the playoffs, with the bats leading the way. But in October, that can't happen. According to Max Gifford, a play-by-play broadcaster for the Brewers' Double-A affiliate, the Biloxi Shuckers, he is not surprised that the approach didn't work. Calling baseball games every day during the regular season and being a part of playoff baseball games, he sees it firsthand. He believes there is more pressure on pitchers to make pitches, and there comes a point when a fastball down the middle to any big leaguer is going to be a home run.
    </p>
